Facial Reconstructions of USS Monitor Sailors
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/monitor-faces.jpg
                    
					Forensic anthropologists have created facial reconstructions based on the skeletons of two sailors who went down with the USS Monitor in 1862. Officials hope the project will help identify the men 150 years after their death. (Credit: LSU University Relations)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Sailors on USS Monitor’s Deck
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/monitor-sailors-on-deck.jpg
                    
					The soldiers died along with 14 fellow crewmembers when the USS Monitor sank in rough seas off Cape Hatteras, North Carolina. None of the other victims have been found. Forty-six men managed to escape the doomed vessel. (Credit: Library of Congress)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Raising of Monitor’s Turret
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/uss-monitor-turret.jpg
                    
					The remains of the unidentified sailors were found inside the USS Monitor’s gun turret, which was recovered during a 2002 expedition. (Credit: Monitor Collection, NOAA)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Skulls of Monitor Sailors
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/uss-monitor-skulls.jpg
                    
					Forensic specialists at Louisiana State University analyzed the two skulls removed from the turret. (Credit: LSU University Relations)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Clay Reconstruction in Progress
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/uss-monitor-clay.jpg
                    
					After taking precise measurements, they crafted features out of clay. (Credit: LSU University Relations)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Completed Clay Reconstruction
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/uss-monitor-clay-2.jpg
                    
					Once the clay models were transformed into plastic replicas, computer-enhanced imaging techniques helped the team complete lifelike depictions of what the sailors might have looked like. (Credit: LSU University Relations)
																                        				  la                                
                        															
							
					Diver at Monitor Wreck Site
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/uss-monitor-wreck.jpg
                    
					Many artifacts from the USS Monitor have been recovered and are now on display at the Mariners' Museum in Newport News, Virginia. The wreck site became the first U.S. national marine sanctuary in 1975. (Credit: Monitor Collection, NOAA)
